About Data Analysis Report

This RMarkdown file contains the report of the data analysis done for the project on building and deploying a stroke prediction model in R. It contains analysis such as data exploration, summary statistics, and building the prediction models. The final report was completed on Sun Jul 21 15:55:45 2024.

Data Description:

According to the World Health Organization (WHO), stroke is the 2nd leading cause of death globally, responsible for approximately 11% of total deaths.

This data set is used to predict whether a patient is likely to get a stroke based on the input parameters like gender, age, various diseases, and smoking status. Each row in the data provides relevant information about the patient.

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing

Explanation of Data Cleaning and Preprocessing:

  1. Handling Missing Values:
    • The bmi column had 201 missing values. To handle these missing values, the median value of the bmi column was used for imputation. This method was chosen to minimize the effect of outliers and ensure the data’s integrity.
  2. Checking for Duplicate Entries:
    • The dataset was checked for duplicate entries, and no duplicates were found. This ensures that each record is unique and no patient data is repeated.
  3. Ensuring Correct Data Types:
    • It was ensured that the bmi column is numeric, and categorical variables such as gender, ever married, work type, residence type, smoking status, and stroke were converted to factors. This conversion is essential for proper handling by machine learning algorithms.

Steps to Clean the Data:

  1. Handle Missing Values:
    • Imputed missing values in the bmi column with the median of the column.
  2. Check for Duplicate Entries:
    • Verified that there are no duplicate entries in the dataset.
  3. Ensure Correct Data Types:
    • Converted categorical variables to factors and numeric variables to appropriate numeric types.

These steps ensured that the dataset is clean, consistent, and ready for the modeling phase. Proper data cleaning and preprocessing are critical to building accurate and reliable prediction models.

Clear Evidence of Data Cleaning

The data cleaning observations are as follows:

  1. Missing Values:
    • The missing values in the bmi column were handled by imputation with the median value.
  2. Duplicate Entries:
    • There are no duplicate entries in the dataset, ensuring that each record is unique.
  3. Data Type Conversions:
    • Categorical variables were correctly converted to factors, and numeric variables were ensured to be numeric.

The dataset contains the following columns:

  • id: Unique identifier for each patient
  • gender: Gender of the patient
  • age: Age of the patient
  • hypertension: Indicates if the patient has hypertension (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • heart_disease: Indicates if the patient has heart disease (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • ever_married: Indicates if the patient has been married
  • work_type: Type of occupation
  • Residence_type: Type of residence (Urban/Rural)
  • avg_glucose_level: Average glucose level in blood
  • bmi: Body Mass Index
  • smoking_status: Smoking status of the patient
  • stroke: Indicates if the patient had a stroke (1 = yes, 0 = no)

Task Two: Build prediction models

Model Building: Data Preparation

Data Partitioning

Data partitioning is the process of splitting the dataset into training and testing sets to evaluate the performance of the machine learning models. This ensures that the models are evaluated on unseen data, providing a reliable measure of their performance.

Dealing with Class Imbalance

Class imbalance occurs when the number of instances of one class significantly outnumbers the other class. In this case, the dataset has more non-stroke cases than stroke cases. To handle this, the SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) method was used. SMOTE generates synthetic samples for the minority class to balance the dataset, improving the model’s ability to detect stroke cases.

Data Normalization and Standardization

Normalization and standardization are techniques used to scale the features to a similar range. This is important for machine learning models to perform optimally, as it ensures that no feature dominates others due to its scale. Normalization scales the data to a range of 0 to 1, while standardization scales the data to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

One-Hot Encoding of Categorical Variables

One-hot encoding is used to convert categorical variables into a format that can be provided to machine learning algorithms to do a better job in prediction. This involves creating binary columns for each category of a categorical variable, ensuring that the model can interpret the categorical data effectively.

Model Building: Classification Models

Cross-Validation and Hyperparameter Tuning

Cross-validation is a technique used to assess the performance of a machine learning model and ensure that it generalizes well to unseen data. It involves partitioning the training data into subsets, training the model on some subsets while validating it on others, and then averaging the results. This helps in selecting the best model and tuning hyperparameters.

Hyperparameter tuning involves adjusting the parameters of the machine learning algorithms to optimize their performance. This is typically done using techniques like grid search or random search over a specified parameter grid.

Building Classification Models

Several classification models were built and evaluated using the training set. These include:

  • Random Forest: An ensemble learning method that constructs multiple decision trees during training and outputs the mode of the classes for classification.
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM): A supervised learning model that finds the hyperplane that best separates the classes in the feature space.

By preparing the data properly and using cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning, robust classification models were built to predict stroke risk effectively. These steps ensure that the models are well-trained and optimized for the best performance on unseen data.

Split the data into training and testing sets

set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(stroke_data$stroke, p = .8, 
                                  list = FALSE, 
                                  times = 1)
stroke_train <- stroke_data[trainIndex,]
stroke_test <- stroke_data[-trainIndex,]

# Ensure levels of factors in test set match the training set
for (col in names(stroke_train)) {
  if (is.factor(stroke_train[[col]])) {
    stroke_test[[col]] <- factor(stroke_test[[col]], levels = levels(stroke_train[[col]]))
  }
}

# Verify no missing values in the training set
if (sum(is.na(stroke_train)) > 0) {
  stop("Training set contains missing values.")
}

Train a Random Forest model

# Train a random forest model
rf_model <- randomForest(stroke ~ ., data = stroke_train, importance = TRUE)

# Print the model

Task Three: Evaluate and select prediction models

Model Evaluation

Evaluation of Models on the Test Set

Metrics for Model Evaluation

The classification models were evaluated on the test set using a variety of metrics, including:

  • Accuracy: The proportion of true results (both true positives and true negatives) among the total number of cases examined.
  • Sensitivity (Recall): The ability of the model to correctly identify true positives (stroke cases).
  • Specificity: The ability of the model to correctly identify true negatives (non-stroke cases).
  • Precision: The proportion of true positives among the predicted positives.
  • F1 Score: The harmonic mean of precision and recall.
  • Area Under the Curve (AUC): The measure of the ability of the model to distinguish between classes.

Model Evaluation Results

The models were evaluated using the test set, and the following results were observed:

  • Random Forest Model:
    • Demonstrated high accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, and F1 score.
    • Showed a high AUC in the ROC analysis, indicating a strong ability to distinguish between stroke and non-stroke cases.
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM) Model:
    • Showed reasonable performance but did not surpass the Random Forest model in terms of accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, or AUC.

Explanation of Best Model Selection

Based on the evaluation metrics, the Random Forest model was selected as the best model for predicting stroke risk due to its superior performance across multiple metrics, including AUC, accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity. These metrics indicate that the Random Forest model is more reliable and effective in identifying both stroke and non-stroke cases compared to the SVM model.

Evaluate models on the testing set

# Ensure the test set has only predictor variables

Task Five: Findings and Conclusions

Model Findings and Conclusions

Based on the evaluation of different machine learning models (Random Forest and SVM), we can draw the following conclusions:

  1. Model Performance:
    • The Random Forest model demonstrated the highest Area Under the Curve (AUC) in the ROC analysis, indicating superior performance in distinguishing between stroke and non-stroke cases.
    • The SVM model performed adequately but did not surpass the performance of the Random Forest model in terms of AUC.
  2. Feature Importance:
    • Age, average glucose level, and BMI were significant predictors of stroke across both models.
    • Lifestyle factors such as smoking status and work type also played important roles in predicting stroke risk.
  3. Class Imbalance Handling:
    • The application of SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) effectively addressed the class imbalance issue, enhancing the models’ ability to detect stroke cases.

Significant Predictors

  1. Age:
    • Older age is a significant predictor of stroke risk.
  2. Average Glucose Level:
    • Higher average glucose levels are associated with an increased risk of stroke.
  3. BMI (Body Mass Index):
    • Both very high and very low BMI values can indicate higher stroke risk.

Lifestyle Factors

  1. Smoking Status:
    • Smoking significantly increases the risk of stroke.
  2. Work Type:
    • Certain occupations or types of work (e.g., sedentary vs. active jobs) can influence stroke risk.

Additional Factors

  1. Hypertension:
    • High blood pressure is a well-known risk factor for stroke.
  2. Heart Disease:
    • The presence of heart disease increases the risk of stroke.
  3. Ever Married:
    • This can be an indicator of social and lifestyle factors that might influence stroke risk.
  4. Residence Type:
    • Urban or rural living conditions might affect access to healthcare and lifestyle, influencing stroke risk.

Considerations for Model Improvement

  1. Medical History:
    • Detailed medical history, including past stroke incidents, family history of stroke, and other comorbid conditions.
  2. Genetic Information:
    • Genetic predispositions to stroke can be a crucial factor.
  3. Detailed Lifestyle Information:
    • More granular data on lifestyle, including diet, physical activity, and alcohol consumption.
  4. Socioeconomic Status:
    • Income, education, and other socioeconomic factors that can influence health outcomes.

Feature Engineering Suggestions

  1. Interaction Terms:
    • Investigate interactions between different features to understand their combined effects on stroke risk.
  2. Advanced Feature Engineering:
    • Use techniques like principal component analysis (PCA) or clustering to extract more meaningful patterns from the data.
  3. Temporal Features:
    • If the data includes time-series information, temporal patterns and trends can be crucial for prediction.

Limitations and Areas for Further Research

  1. Data Limitations:
    • The dataset lacks detailed medical history and genetic information, which could be critical for more accurate stroke prediction.
    • The presence of missing values in the BMI column required imputation, which may introduce some level of bias.
  2. Model Generalizability:
    • The models were trained on a specific dataset, and their performance might vary when applied to different populations or regions. Therefore, external validation with diverse datasets is necessary.
  3. Feature Engineering:
    • Future research could focus on more advanced feature engineering techniques to extract meaningful patterns from the data.
    • Investigating the interactions between features and their combined effects on stroke risk could provide deeper insights.
  4. Ethical and Privacy Considerations:
    • Ensure that the deployment of the prediction model adheres to ethical guidelines and respects patient privacy.
    • Implement robust data security measures to protect sensitive patient information.
